      <!-- General Optimization Tips -->
      <h2>General PC Optimization Tips</h2>

      <h3>NVIDIA Control Panel Settings</h3>
      <p>Open NVIDIA Control Panel → Manage 3D Settings → Global Settings and apply these changes for the best competitive experience:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Power Management Mode:</strong> Prefer Maximum Performance — prevents GPU from throttling clocks to save power during gameplay.</li>
        <li><strong>Low Latency Mode:</strong> Ultra — queues only one frame ahead, reducing input lag by 10-20ms. Use this for games without NVIDIA Reflex support.</li>
        <li><strong>Texture Filtering Quality:</strong> High Performance — slight quality reduction for a small FPS gain.</li>
        <li><strong>Vertical Sync:</strong> Off — always disable globally to prevent added input lag.</li>
        <li><strong>Max Frame Rate:</strong> Set 3-5 FPS below your monitor's refresh rate if you experience tearing without V-Sync (e.g., 141 for 144Hz).</li>
        <li><strong>Preferred Refresh Rate:</strong> Highest Available — ensures your monitor runs at its maximum refresh rate in all games.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>AMD Radeon Software Settings</h3>
      <p>Open AMD Radeon Software → Gaming → Global Graphics and apply:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Radeon Anti-Lag:</strong> Enabled — AMD's equivalent to NVIDIA Reflex, reduces input lag.</li>
        <li><strong>Radeon Chill:</strong> Disabled — this caps FPS dynamically, which is bad for competitive games.</li>
        <li><strong>Texture Filtering Quality:</strong> Performance.</li>
        <li><strong>Wait for Vertical Refresh:</strong> Always Off.</li>
        <li><strong>Surface Format Optimization:</strong> Enabled — minor quality trade for better performance.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Windows Optimization</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Game Mode:</strong> Enable in Settings → Gaming → Game Mode. Prevents background updates and allocates resources to your game.</li>
        <li><strong>Hardware-Accelerated GPU Scheduling:</strong> Enable in Settings → Display → Graphics → Default graphics settings. Reduces latency on supported GPUs.</li>
        <li><strong>Power Plan:</strong> Set to High Performance or Ultimate Performance in Control Panel → Power Options.</li>
        <li><strong>Background Apps:</strong> Disable unnecessary startup apps in Task Manager → Startup tab. Discord, browser tabs, and RGB software eat CPU and RAM.</li>
        <li><strong>Xbox Game Bar:</strong> Disable in Settings → Gaming → Xbox Game Bar unless you need capture. The overlay adds minor overhead.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Monitor Settings</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Refresh Rate:</strong> Set to maximum in Windows Display Settings → Advanced Display → Refresh Rate. Many monitors default to 60Hz even if they support 144Hz+.</li>
        <li><strong>Overdrive/Response Time:</strong> Set to the fastest mode without visible inverse ghosting (usually the second-highest setting).</li>
        <li><strong>Game Mode:</strong> Enable on your monitor's OSD — this bypasses image processing and reduces display lag.</li>
        <li><strong>Color Mode:</strong> Use the FPS or Competitive preset if available — these boost brightness in dark areas, making enemies easier to spot.</li>
      </ul>

